Welcome to September's Turing-Roche newsletter! We hope you managed to have a break over the summer. Here you can find what's new in the Turing-Roche strategic partnership and opportunities, events and news from both The Alan Turing Institute and Roche.

Our [five year partnership](http://elink.turing.ac.) was set up officially in June 2021 following a successful [Data Study Group](http://elink.turing.ac._X2NsZGVlPVpObkp3RnpkTUwwSTlSUXZBZ1d6elA2SmdTOTc5RVMtRjUza0xUM05UOW1GOVJjV3l1UDVrWHUyeERPbXoyMHomcmVjaXBpZW50aWQ9Y29udGFjdC00ODgwYThjMzkyM2NlYzExOGM2MjAwMjI0ODQzNGZlYi04OWFjYjdhZDExMjc0YjhiYjM1ZDZmMzBlNjgxYjdlZCZlc2lkPTM4MTMwNmU5LWUxMmQtZWQxMS05ZGIxLTAwMjI0ODQyNWU4NSJ9/D_nFsWaf7UvTH2Z28B4ztg) and a 12 week research project on lung cancer treatment. Our 'North Star' is **to enable the generation of insights to better understand patient and disease heterogeneity and its relevance to clinical outcomes at an unprecedented level of precision in order to improve clinical care. **

We will be covering multiple activities over the five years to work towards our North Star, as well as building strong connections and collaborations between the Alan Turing Institute, Roche and the wider community.

If you have anything you'd like featured in a future newsletter then please get in touch with Vicky Hellon, Community Manager for the partnership at vhellon@turing.ac.uk

If you would like to share this newsletter with relevant colleagues please direct them to sign-up [here](http://elink.turing.ac._).

## Turing-Roche Strategic Partnership Updates

 ![](https://file-eu.clickdimensions.com/turingacuk-ap7zg/files/photo-1457530378978-8bac673b8062.jfif) 

### Partnership launches new funding call on Predictive Modelling

We're excited to launch our second funding call for the partnership! This year we are exploring the topic of predictive modelling in the context of uncertainty and heterogeneity in biomedical data and are inviting proposals from researchers. Projects can either be main projects- running for 12-18 months and aimed at senior researchers, or pilot projects- running for approx 6 months for early career researchers looking to pursue proof-of-concept research.

You can find out more about the funding call and how to apply [here](http://elink.turing.ac.-t7_1EiII37f0Gfg). The deadline for applications is the **14 November**. We also will be running an information and Q&A session on the 19 September which you can register for [here](http://elink.turing.ac._X2NsZGVlPVpObkp3RnpkTUwwSTlSUXZBZ1d6elA2SmdTOTc5RVMtRjUza0xUM05UOW1GOVJjV3l1UDVrWHUyeERPbXoyMHomcmVjaXBpZW50aWQ9Y29udGFjdC00ODgwYThjMzkyM2NlYzExOGM2MjAwMjI0ODQzNGZlYi04OWFjYjdhZDExMjc0YjhiYjM1ZDZmMzBlNjgxYjdlZCZlc2lkPTM4MTMwNmU5LWUxMmQtZWQxMS05ZGIxLTAwMjI0ODQyNWU4NSJ9/gA9jZgU0n-eEpUanB7QjfA), alongside a collaborative workshop which you can find out more info on [here](http://elink.turing.ac._Wj7HUg).

### Knowledge Share Series Event: OMICs

**12 September 2022**

Join us for our [partnership knowledge share series](http://elink.turing.ac._X2NsZGVlPVpObkp3RnpkTUwwSTlSUXZBZ1d6elA2SmdTOTc5RVMtRjUza0xUM05UOW1GOVJjV3l1UDVrWHUyeERPbXoyMHomcmVjaXBpZW50aWQ9Y29udGFjdC00ODgwYThjMzkyM2NlYzExOGM2MjAwMjI0ODQzNGZlYi04OWFjYjdhZDExMjc0YjhiYjM1ZDZmMzBlNjgxYjdlZCZlc2lkPTM4MTMwNmU5LWUxMmQtZWQxMS05ZGIxLTAwMjI0ODQyNWU4NSJ9/LSxgRn_kFLi9yBcV5TVBMQ). Our aim is to bring together members of the Turing and Roche networks and the wider scientific community to share different academic and industry perspectives on areas related to patient/treatment heterogeneity and data science more generally.

September's event is on the 12th on the theme of omics. We'll be hearing from Dr Marius Rene Garmhausen, Principal Data Scientist in Personalised Healthcare at Roche and Dr Andrew Holding, Lecturer in Biomedical Science, University of York and former Turing fellow. You can find out more and register for the event [here](http://elink.turing.ac._X2NsZGVlPVpObkp3RnpkTUwwSTlSUXZBZ1d6elA2SmdTOTc5RVMtRjUza0xUM05UOW1GOVJjV3l1UDVrWHUyeERPbXoyMHomcmVjaXBpZW50aWQ9Y29udGFjdC00ODgwYThjMzkyM2NlYzExOGM2MjAwMjI0ODQzNGZlYi04OWFjYjdhZDExMjc0YjhiYjM1ZDZmMzBlNjgxYjdlZCZlc2lkPTM4MTMwNmU5LWUxMmQtZWQxMS05ZGIxLTAwMjI0ODQyNWU4NSJ9/OTZQbB-gE1dQNt9d6wVpvA).

You can also catch-up on previous recordings of our events at our [YouTube channel](http://elink.turing.ac.).

### Job: Senior Postdoctoral Research Associate

**Deadline: 9 September 2022 23:59**

We are hiring a second Senior Postdoctoral Research Associate for the partnership. The post is full-time for 3 years and will give the post holder experience working closely with both Turing and Roche to help shape direction of the partnership, as well as the freedom to develop their own area of aligned research under mentorship from senior leaders in both academia and industry.

More info at the job ad [here](http://elink.turing.ac.)- be aware applications close on the** 9th September**.

### New Demystifying Video Series

We have launched the first video in our new 'demystification' series. The series aims to demystify concepts relevant to the partnership's research aims. Our first video is from our Senior Postdoctoral Research Associate [Tapabrata (Rohan) Chakraborty](http://elink.turing.ac.) who tackles Bayesian Estimation- you can watch it [here](http://elink.turing.ac.-IdCd-pzc16KA). If you have an idea for a demystifying video or you'd be interested in recording one, then please get in touch with our Community Manager Vicky Hellon at vhellon@turing.ac.uk 

## Current Opportunities at The Alan Turing Institute and Roche

 ![](https://file-eu.clickdimensions.com/turingacuk-ap7zg/files/group_study_working__0.jpg) 

### Turing Institute Training Course: Introduction to Research Software Engineering with Python

**31 October- 11 November 2022**

The Turing Institute's Research Engineering Group are running a free online training course introducing Research Software Engineering in Python. You will learn how to construct reliable, readable, efficient research software in a collaborative environment. The emphasis is on practical techniques, tips and technologies to effectively build and maintain complex code. Find out more info and how to apply [here](http://elink.turing.ac._-WiIQVuyhXU7w).

### 9 month PhD Internship at Roche's Clinical Imaging Group

Roche are recruiting a PhD student for their RiSE (Roche internships for scientific exchange) programme. It offers talented postgraduate PhD and medical degree students the opportunity to be fully integrated into the industry R&D environment. As a RiSE student you will enhance your competencies, gain valuable work experience with Roche, and eventually become part of a world-wide network of RiSE Alumni. This position is based in Basel, Switzerland in the Clinical Imaging Group in Biomarkers and Translational Technologies, with the aim of developing machine learning models to predict Huntington's disease progression and treatment response using imaging, molecular and clinical data. More info and how to apply [here](http://elink.turing.ac.).

### #VizTIG- Turing's Visualization Symposium

**13-14 September 2022**

The Turing Institute's [Visulization Interest Group](http://elink.turing.ac._X2NsZGVlPVpObkp3RnpkTUwwSTlSUXZBZ1d6elA2SmdTOTc5RVMtRjUza0xUM05UOW1GOVJjV3l1UDVrWHUyeERPbXoyMHomcmVjaXBpZW50aWQ9Y29udGFjdC00ODgwYThjMzkyM2NlYzExOGM2MjAwMjI0ODQzNGZlYi04OWFjYjdhZDExMjc0YjhiYjM1ZDZmMzBlNjgxYjdlZCZlc2lkPTM4MTMwNmU5LWUxMmQtZWQxMS05ZGIxLTAwMjI0ODQyNWU4NSJ9/L8x07ltps0p4_mEKh6bUrQ) are hosting their symposium at Kings's College London. Join in-person or online to hear contrasting perspectives on data visulization and think with us into the future. Registration [here](http://elink.turing.ac.).

### PANACEA: PANdemic Ai Claim vEracity Assessment Workshop

**14 September 2022**

This in-person workshop at the Alan Turing Institute will present the main findings of the PANACEA project which developed novel methods for veracity assessment of claims unverified at the time of posting, by integrating information from multiple sources. In addition to presenting project outcomes, the organisers would like to use this workshop as an opportunity for participants to discuss the open challenges in claim veracity assessment and feasible mitigation strategies to combat the propagation of misinformation. Register [here](http://elink.turing.ac.).

### Open Data Saves Lives- Unconference 2: Reproducible Analytical Pipelines (RAPs)

**20 September 2022**

#OpenDataSavesLives is driving open innovation with data. Their aim is to help reduce inequalities by creating for the first time a true network of collaborators and resources in the open. This in-person event in Leeds aims to showcase examples, share knowledge and use cases where RAPs have been developed, with a particular focus on the challenges teams have faced and how to resolve them. More info and how to register [here](http://elink.turing.ac.).

### Royal Society of Biology Policy Lates: Tackling inequity in Clinical Research

**20 September 2022**

The Royal Society of Biology are hosting an online Policy Lates panel discussion exploring how addressing inequity in clinical research design can benefit public health and wellbeing. More information and how to register [here](http://elink.turing.ac.).

### Roche Event: Diversity in clinical trials- Why including every eligible patient matters

**21 September 2022**

Roche are hosting a panel discussion on the importance of diversity in clinical trials. Michelle Rohrer, Global Head of Regulatory at Roche will be joined by expert panelists to reflect on the barriers and surface ideas and actions to remove them. Find out more and register [here](http://elink.turing.ac._X2NsZGVlPVpObkp3RnpkTUwwSTlSUXZBZ1d6elA2SmdTOTc5RVMtRjUza0xUM05UOW1GOVJjV3l1UDVrWHUyeERPbXoyMHomcmVjaXBpZW50aWQ9Y29udGFjdC00ODgwYThjMzkyM2NlYzExOGM2MjAwMjI0ODQzNGZlYi04OWFjYjdhZDExMjc0YjhiYjM1ZDZmMzBlNjgxYjdlZCZlc2lkPTM4MTMwNmU5LWUxMmQtZWQxMS05ZGIxLTAwMjI0ODQyNWU4NSJ9/ckMw53_j9b4arYLHP1n3GQ).

### ELIXIR Bioinformatics Industry Forum: Enabling Ecosystems for Machine Learning in the Life Sciences

**11 October 2022**

The ELIXIR Bioinformatics Industry Forum (EBIF) is a one-day event and aims to bring together the community of bioinformaticians to discuss visionary ideas, bottlenecks and solutions to some of the major challenges in the data-driven life science sector. This year's EBIF focus is on making Machine Learning robust and reproducible for the Life Sciences. The programme includes a mixture of presentations from industry and academia that will lead to panel discussions. Find out more [here](http://elink.turing.ac._X2NsZGVlPVpObkp3RnpkTUwwSTlSUXZBZ1d6elA2SmdTOTc5RVMtRjUza0xUM05UOW1GOVJjV3l1UDVrWHUyeERPbXoyMHomcmVjaXBpZW50aWQ9Y29udGFjdC00ODgwYThjMzkyM2NlYzExOGM2MjAwMjI0ODQzNGZlYi04OWFjYjdhZDExMjc0YjhiYjM1ZDZmMzBlNjgxYjdlZCZlc2lkPTM4MTMwNmU5LWUxMmQtZWQxMS05ZGIxLTAwMjI0ODQyNWU4NSJ9/kyi82NjqgltEBhrs7ZpKlQ).

### The Northern Data Debates: A healthy trust in data? Personalised health and preventative care

**26 October 2022**

Sponsored by the Turing Institute, the National Innovation Centre for Data and Newcastle Data, the debates are spirited conversations that bring world-leading experts together from a variety of backgrounds to discuss issues of critical interest where data science, artificial intelligence and the real world collide. This debate explores the latest developments in data-driven healthcare and debates the promises and challenges that surround innovations. More info and registration [here](http://elink.turing.ac.__3zep36WywQtYkiqBjJw).

### Call for papers: Social Determinants of Health (SDOH) Extraction through Natural Language Processing

**Submission deadline 5 December 2022**

JAMIA (Journal of Informatics in Health and Biomedicine) is inviting NLP methodology papers that explore the extraction of SDOH information from text, including clinical notes, transcribed patient visits, social media, and other sources for a focus issue. Find out more [here](http://elink.turing.ac._).

### Call for position papers: NeurIPS 2022 Workshop on Causality for Real-world Impact

**Submission deadline 30 September 2022**

The 2022 NeurIPS Workshop on Causal Machine Learning for Real-World Impact is calling for contributions combining causality and machine learning, with a view on using these methods to solve real-world problems with practical impact. They are inviting researchers to submit position papers about real-world causal problems, methodological contributions applying machine learning to solve causal questions, applications of these methods to specific real-world problems, as well as tools to ease the applications by practitioners. More information [here](http://elink.turing.ac.-HMg).

### Job: Research Associate in Testing AI Ethics at Kings College London

**Deadline 15 September 2022**

Kings College London are hiring a postdoctoral reseacher on testing ethical aspects of AI. These include testing aspects such as fairness and bias, as well as privacy and explainability. The successful applicant will be working within a vigorous multi-disciplinary environment of the Trustworthy Autonomous System program with researchers across many disciplines designing and verifying the autonomous systems of the future. Find out more and how to apply [here](http://elink.turing.ac._-iS2_rgkSbN5wZIabCA).

### Job: Senior Research Fellow in Medical Statistics/Data Science/Epidemiology at University of Oxford

**Deadline 16 September 2022**

University of Oxford are hiring two Senior Research Fellows to work in a team with Professor Julia Hippisley-Cox on a research programme in medical research using very large clinical research databases and at the interface between epidemiology, medical statistics, data science and clinical medicine as part of the Primary Care Epidemiology Research Group. More info and how to apply [here](http://elink.turing.ac.).

### Job: Professor of Artificial Intelligence, University of Manchester

**Deadline 02 October 2022**

The University of Manchester is seeking to appoint a Chair in Artificial Intelligence to develop their research programme in Manchester, building on existing research strengths in computational biology and health data science. Find out more and how to apply [here](http://elink.turing.ac._jbh-dQ).

## Publication of the Month

 ![](https://file-eu.clickdimensions.com/turingacuk-ap7zg/files/patrick-tomasso-oaqk7qqnh_c-unsplash2.jpg) 

**Outcome Indistinguishability**

September's publication of the month has been chosen by Rohan, our Senior Postdoctoral Research Associate. Published in Proceedings of the 53rd Annual ACM SIGACT Symposium on Theory of Computing, [this paper](http://elink.turing.ac.) by Prof Cynthia Dwork and colleagues explores Outcome Indistinguishability, an approach arising from complexity theory that can compare predictive models based on individual outcomes, and hence has potential in personalised healthcare.

Prof Dwork also gave a Turing Lecture on 'What are your chances- the defining problem of AI' last year which you can catchup on [here](http://elink.turing.ac._xMbUJVrCHviA).
